Promise :-

Promise JavaScript में asynchronous operations को handle करने का तरीका हैMtlab hamko future me result milega Vo  complete higa yha fir Fail iske Reuslt ke baad pata chalata hai 


2️⃣ Promise की 3 States
1️⃣ Pending → अभी task चल रहा है
2️⃣ Fulfilled → task success
3️⃣ Rejected → task fail
Promise JavaScript में asynchronous operations handle करने के लिए use होता है।
इसकी 3 states होती हैं: Pending, Fulfilled, Rejected।
Promise से callback hell avoid होता है और code readable बनता है।

4️⃣ Promise कब use करते हैं

जब asynchronous work करना हो:

API call (fetch)
setTimeout
Database request
File reading





Example :
function orderPizza() {
    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
        console.log("🍕 Pizza order liya...");
        
        setTimeout(() => {
            let pizzaAvailable = Math.random() > 0.3; // 70% chance available
            
            if(pizzaAvailable) {
                resolve({
                    name: "Margherita",
                    price: 299,
                    message: "Pizza deliver ho gaya!"
                });
            } else {
                reject({
                    error: "Pizza out of stock!",
                    alternatives: ["Onion Pizza", "Corn Pizza"]
                });
            }
        }, 3000);
    });
}
orderPizza().then((pizza) => {
    console.log("✅ Success:", pizza.message);
    console.log("Pizza:", pizza.name, "Price:", pizza.price);
});


1. then() method - Success handle
2. catch() method - Error handle
3. finally() method - Hamesha chalega
// ❌ Callback Hell (Purana tarika)
getUser(1, (user) => {
    getPosts(user.id, (posts) => {
        getComments(posts[0].id, (comments) => {
            getLikes(comments[0].id, (likes) => {
                console.log(likes);
            });
        });
    });
});

// ✅ Promise Chaining (Naya tarika)
getUser(1)
    .then(user => getPosts(user.id))
    .then(posts => getComments(posts[0].id))
    .then(comments => getLikes(comments[0].id))
    .then(likes => console.log(likes))
    .catch(error => console.log(error));





 Promise Methods (Advanced)
1. Promise.all() - Sab ek saath


// Jab sab promises complete hon tab chahiye
const userPromise = fetch('/api/user');
const postsPromise = fetch('/api/posts');
const friendsPromise = fetch('/api/friends');

Promise.all([userPromise, postsPromise, friendsPromise])
    .then(([user, posts, friends]) => {
        console.log("Sab data mil gaya:", {user, posts, friends});
    })
    .catch(error => {
        console.log("Ek bhi fail hua to sab fail:", error);
    });


2. Promise.race() - Jo pehle aaye

// Jo promise pehle complete ho (chahe resolve ya reject)
const fastAPI = fetch('/api/fast');
const slowAPI = fetch('/api/slow');

Promise.race([fastAPI, slowAPI])
    .then(winner => {
        console.log("Pehle wala complete:", winner);
    });



3. Promise.any() - Jo pehle succeed kare	
// Jo pehle RESOLVE ho, reject ignore karo
const api1 = fetch('/api1'); // Slow but working
const api2 = fetch('/api2'); // Fast but failing
const api3 = fetch('/api3'); // Medium, working




4. Promise.allSettled() - Sabka status
Promise.any([api1, api2, api3])
    .then(firstSuccess => {
        console.log("Pehla successful API:", firstSuccess);
    })
    .catch(error => {
        console.log("Sab fail ho gaye:", error);
    });



✅ Promise Cheatsheet


// CREATE
const p = new Promise((res, rej) => { res("ok"); });

// CONSUME
p.then(value => {}).catch(err => {}).finally(() => {});

// CHAIN
p.then(f1).then(f2).then(f3).catch(errHandler);

// COMBINE
Promise.all([p1, p2])      // All or nothing
Promise.race([p1, p2])     // First one
Promise.any([p1, p2])      // First success
Promise.allSettled([p1, p2]) // All statuses

// CONVERT
Promise.resolve("value")   // Creates resolved promise
Promise.reject("error")    // Creates rejected promise





